{
  "style": "APA",
  "texts": [
    "Specifically, large language models (LLMs) trained on past human forecasts are beginning to achieve performance levels that approach, though do not yet surpass, human forecasters.",
    "In fact, \"crowds\" of LLMs have sometimes reached the accuracy of human superforecasters (Schoenegger, Tuminauskaite, Park and Tetlock; 2024).",
    "A seemingly promising development is the use of LLMs as forecasting assistants: recent studies show that human superforecasting accuracy improves by 23% when LLMs are used as supportive tools, without diminishing forecast diversity (Schoenegger, Park, Karger, Trott and Tetlock; 2024).",
    "These models are also beneficial in refining prediction market data by aggregating and weighing various predictions to produce more accurate forecasts (Gruen et al.; 2023).",
    "However, some studies suggest more conservative expectations (Abolghasemi et al.; 2024), highlighting the need for caution when deploying these as assistants."
  ],
